Tightening the Grid on Fire Effects Using NEON 1-m LiDAR and Hyperspectral Reflectance Datasets: A Case Study of the 2016 Chimney Tops 2 Wildfire, Great Smoky Mountains National Park, USA¶

Authors: Eric Gottlieb and Heidi Yoon¶

Project Partner: Dr. Nayani Ilangakoon, Earth Lab¶

Introduction¶

Wildland fire is a fundamental ecosystem disturbance process (e.g., McLauchlan et al., 2020) that has influenced our planet’s biosphere since at least the Silurian Period (Glasspool et al, 2004) ca. 420 million years ago. At present, fire-prone landscapes exist on every continent except Antarctica. Within the United States, the vast majority of wildland fires are human-caused, and thus there has been a step-change increase in their occurrence and effects on natural systems as human population has expanded in numbers and geographical extent (e.g., Balch et al., 2017). Naturally occurring fires (i.e. lightning-caused) are likewise problematic for ecosystems and societies, as recently exemplified by an August 2020 widespread lightning event in California which ignited hundreds of fires that burned >6000 km2, destroyed several thousand structures, and killed at least 25 civilians. Regardless of initial cause, “managing” wildland fire has become one of the foremost challenges for societies that exist in or near fire-prone landscapes.

As a corollary, the ecological functionality of fire-prone (and fire-dependent) landscapes is in many places at the mercy of human societies that rely on the ecosystem services of these landscapes, but also view wildland fire as a nuisance or threat and have thus excluded fire in recent historical times. Herein lies a fundamental problem for these coupled natural-social systems, as exclusion of fire from fire-prone landscapes tends to drive the natural system towards greater extremes of variability in subsequent disturbance (i.e., high-severity fires), which in turn has greater potential to have catastrophic effects on human society and fundamentally alter the relied-upon characteristics of the ecosystem (e.g., Siedl et al., 2016; Spies et al., 2017). Accordingly, much thought and effort over the past several decades has gone towards how to minimize the risk of catastrophic fire to societies (e.g., Calkin et al., 2014). However, balancing needs on both sides of the coupled natural-social systems equation presents its own set of social, political and economic challenges.

Understanding wildland fire’s effects on an ecosystem is a complex challenge that can be influenced by a variety of environmental conditions extant before, during and after a wildland fire’s occurrence. Datasets that can quantify these conditions have become increasingly available in modern times due to the proliferation of high spatial resolution remote sensing-based observational methods (e.g., National Ecological Observatory Network, aka NEON). Thus, these advances provide emerging scientific opportunities to study cause and effect relationships between environmental conditions and wildland fire effects, as long as we can develop the ability to use remotely-sensed datasets to accurately describe key environmental variables. By focusing on empirically-derived fire effects data from actual wildland fire events, this approach provides an important database for predicting fire effects associated with future (planned or unplanned) wildland fire occurrences. Furthermore, these high resolution data also present an opportunity to determine the accuracy/validity of coarser scale (and more widely available) legacy datasets.

For this project, we have focused on basic principles of fire behavior (fuels, weather, topography) to establish a simple set of environmental variables to relate to fire effects observable by remote sensing methodologies. The study site has been chosen based on the availability of high spatial resolution (1-m) topography (LiDAR) and reflectance (NEON hyperspectral) data for a wildfire event that burned a relatively large area with extreme intensity during a several hour-long period of near hurricane-force winds. Our objectives of the study are:

  1. Spatially quantify post-fire vegetation recovery using hyperspectral reflectance data across the burn area.
  2. Relate the observed variability in fire effects (i.e., Objective #1) to environmental variables (e.g, fuel loading, alignment of slope and wind) that theoretically increase or decrease fire intensity.
  3. Assess the precision/accuracy/scalability of legacy lower spatial/spectral resolution datasets in comparison to higher resolution data used in this study.

Background1¶

The Chimney Tops 2 wildfire was a human-caused wildfire that was detected in Great Smoky Mountains National Park on November 23rd, 2016. Despite unseasonably dry conditions across the region, an initial management decision was made to allow the fire to burn within a 400 acre (160 ha) containment zone due to the fire being located in extremely challenging terrain (Fig. 1). The plan primarily relied on natural barriers such as creeks and trails to stop ground/surface fire spread within the containment zone. On November 27th, after several days of low-moderate intensity fire behavior, the fire began to burn with more intensity and escaped the containment zone by the morning of November 28th.

  • Figure 1. Chimney Tops 2 wildfire general origin area. (A) Low intensity burning conditions in rugged terrain around the Chimney Tops at 11 AM on November 26. Image source: NPS Chimney Tops 2 Fire Review (link). (B) Map view of Chimney Tops 2 fire spread progression within containment zone (yellow polygon trace) from November 23-27, 2016. Blue line features are creeks. Solid gray line features are roads. Dashed gray lines are trails. Image source: Chimney Tops 2 Fire After Action Review (link).

Extremely windy conditions on November 28th coupled with the unseasonable dry fuel conditions led to rapid rates of spread and extreme fire behavior, resulting in the fire growing in size from a couple hundred acres on the morning of the 28th to ~17,000 acres by 2 AM on November 29th, burning through the city of Gatlinburg during its explosive growth (Fig. 2).

  • Figure 2. Time-based progression of fire size (upper plot) and weather conditions (lower plot) with inset showing final fire area, from Chimney Tops 2 Fire After Action Review document. Note change in vertical scale on fire size overnight from November 27th to 28th. Fire was detected on Wednesday, November 23rd. Figure source (link).

In the late morning to early afternoon of the 28th, lofted embers carried by the wind from the main fire front started numerous spot fires up to 5 miles ahead of the fire origin area and the firestorm encroached upon the city of Gatlinburg and surroundings (Fig. 3). By 6 PM winds had become strong enough to damage power lines and start additional new fires ahead of the main fire, but the main Chimney Tops 2 fire front soon enveloped these new starts. A massive evacuation effort was ongoing in the early evening as the fire burned through Gatlinburg and towards Pigeon Forge. By 10 PM on the 28th a light rain was reported over parts of the fire and by 2 AM on the 29th steady rain had begun to fall, effectively ending the threat of additional wildland fire growth. The tallied loss of life and property from this catastrophic event amounted to 14 civilian fatalities and 2500 structures destroyed or damaged.

  • Figure 3. Fire conditions in the Gatlinburg area in the evening of November 28th. (A) Wind-carried embers responsible for starting numerous spot fires ahead of the main firefront. (B) Main fire front encroaching on the central Gatlinburg area. Image sources: Chimney Tops 2 Fire After Action Review (link).

In addition to the destruction of property and loss of human lives, the Chimney Tops 2 Fire disturbed the ecological systems within the park. After the 2016 wildfire, to this day, plant and animal communities are still recovering in the burned area. Currently, the summit to Chimney Tops mountain is inaccessible as much of the trees and soils were removed during the fire, and regrowth is still ongoing. One radio-collared bear was reported by the National Park Service to have died due to the fire, however since the fire, bears, turkeys, and other wildlife have been observed in the burned area. In addition to these qualitative indicators of ecosystem recovery, Great Smoky Mountains National Park also contains a NEON Field Site that was established in late 2015, which has been surveyed by NEON’s Aerial Observation Platform that has created an outstanding resource of high spatial resolution LiDAR and hyperspectral data.

1Information and figure material about fire conditions from Chimney Tops 2 Fire Review and After Action Review, hosted by Wildland Fire Lessons Learned Center website.

Previous Work¶

Previously, a study using Landsat multispectral imagery and a National Park Service digital elevation model showed that the burn severity and its spatial variation in the 2016 Chimney Tops 2 region were mostly influenced by the topography and vegetation properties (He, 2018). The burn severity was assessed using surface reflectance data collected by the Landsat 8 Operational Land Imager with 30-nm spectral resolution for the red and near-infrared (NIR) bands and 180-nm spectral resolution for the shortwave-infrared (SWIR) band. Given the spectral resolution of Landsat imagery, spectral features of vegetation and burned areas are unable to be resolved. Instead He., 2018 used extensive field data from the Great Smoky Mountains National Park vegetation database to map the burn severity with vegetation communities. In addition, since forest structures and vegetation recovery typically vary at spatial resolution less than 5 meters (Meng, et al. 2017), the 30-m spatial resolution of the surface reflectance data measured by Landsat 8 limited the ability to characterize the post-fire landscape of the Chimney Tops 2 Fire.

As part of Objective #1, we will quantify the post-fire vegetation recovery using hyperspectral reflectance data obtained by the NEON Airborne Observation Platform (AOP) imaging spectrometer (NEON Spectrometer orthorectified surface directional reflectance - mosaic: DP3.30006.001), which measures 426 spectral bands from 383.5343nm to 2511.8945nm with a spectral resolution of 5nm. Using the hyperspectral reflectance data, we will conduct a vegetation analysis, where we will calculate the burn severity using three different vegetation indices (as shown in the Workflow below). The spectral resolution allows us to use narrower spectral features to identify vegetation and burned areas.

Because the spatial resolution of the NEON reflectance data is 1 meter, we aim to study the burn severity and recovery of the Chimney Tops 2 Fire at a finer scale. Typically burn severity is broadly defined in levels from low to high. The finer spatial resolution will allow us to resolve burn severity at very high resolution after the fire, hence, its impact on ecosystem recovery. The high spatial and spectral resolution will further allow us to use spectral mixture analysis to classify the components within the burned region into separate components, such as, which sections contain green growth [green], standing dead or dormant vegetation [deadwood], and burned areas [char]. In addition, NEON spectrometer data also allows us to possibly identify vegetation species remotely, as shown previously by Meng et al., 2018. All in all, analyzing how the burn components vary over time will allow us to quantify the recovery of the forest.

Workflow¶

Here is the overall workflow for the Case Study of the 2016 Chimney Tops 2 Wildfire:¶

A few shapefiles available from different sources are used in the analysis for reference and spatial analysis. The boundary of Great Smoky Mountains National Park is downloaded from the National Park Service and is used for reference imagery. The perimeter of the Chimney Tops 2 Fire is downloaded from the “Monitoring Trends in Burn Severity” (MTBS) program website, and is used both for reference and as a vector object for clipping larger raster datasets.

At 1-meter spatial resolution, we will spatially quantify the post-fire vegetation recovery (Objective #1) in a series of steps. First, we will calculate the pre- and post-fire vegetation indices using the normalized burn ratio (NBR), the normalized difference vegetation index (NDVI), and the modified soil-adjusted vegetation index (MSAVI). Next, we will determine the vegetation index that best discriminates between burned and unburned areas in the Chimney Tops region using the random forests algorithm (Breiman, L. 2001). Then using the NEON reflectance data and field data for vegetation type and cover for Great Smoky Mountains National Park (NEON Plant presence and percent cover: DP1.10058.001), we will build a spectral library in order to conduct a spectral band analysis. In this blog post, we share preliminary results for Pre/Post-Fire Vegetation Indices in the 1-meter Spatial Resolution Recovery below.

Objective #2 deals with quantifying key environmental variables in the fire environment using 1m (LiDAR Digital Elevation Model) spatial resolution data for topography, 30-m (LANDFIRE grids) spatial resolution data for fuels, and time series data (RAWS wind direction) for weather. Understanding the burned area antecedent physiographic and biophysical conditions for the Chimney Tops 2 Fire allows us to relate variability in fire effects to these environmental variables that theoretically affected the fire’s intensity. The background presented about how the fire spread on November 28th offers a qualitative indicator of the spread vector (generally south to north and overall from higher elevation to lower elevation), which we will quantify by determining the average wind direction from the Indian Grave Remote Automated Weather Station (RAWS) site on November 28th (with the assumption that wind direction is a proxy for spread direction).

The spread direction is used in conjunction with 1-m NEON LiDAR Elevation data (NEON Elevation- LiDAR: DP3.30024.001) to classify slopes as a function of their alignment with the wind direction, which is an important factor in fire intensity. Theoretically the most intense fire behavior based on wind and slope alone would have occurred in places where the wind was blowing directly upslope (i.e., azimuth of wind and aspect are subequal) because convective heating from , which we classify as head fire environments. Conversely, in locations where the wind was blowing downslope (i.e., ~180 degrees between wind azimuth and aspect), fire behavior is theoretically expected to be least intense (because the site should be sheltered from wind and convective preheating is minimal), which we classify as backing fire environments. The intermediate condition between head and backing fire environments would have occurred on slopes where the aspect was orthogonal to the wind direction, which we classify as flanking fire. The raster reclassification approach we use for this step is as follows:

  • Head fire environment: Aspect - Wind Azimuth >-45 and <45
  • Flanking fire environment: Aspect - Wind Azimuth (>45 and <135) or (<-45 and >-135)
  • Backing fire environment: Aspect - Wind Azimuth >135 or <-135

A secondary classification using LiDAR data can be made based on steepness of slope. Head fire environments with the steepest slopes theoretically represent the areas of highest intensity. Based on established research, we will classify slopes >25 degrees in head fire environments as representing the maximum intensity environment as one end member, whereas slopes between 10-20 degrees in backing fire environments are thought to represent minimal burning conditions and are an opposite end member (e.g., Butler et al., 2007). Having these two end members allows us to incorporate a third variable into our analysis- that being fuels (i.e, vegetation type and condition)- to test how post-fire recovery correlates to theoretical burn intensity.

Mapping the reference conditions biophysical setting (LANDFIRE BPS) of the Chimney Tops fire area and how the vegetation has departed from its historical conditions (LANDFIRE VDEP)) allows us to focus on forested areas that have experienced the most (or least) departure from their natural range of variability. The key hypothesis that will be tested is whether post-fire recovery in head fire environments on steep slopes show significant differences from backing fire environments on moderate slopes in areas with similar biophysical and vegetation departure characteristics. Our analysis will ultimately involve plotting results of the three different vegetation indices measured in Objective #1 versus our various environmental variable end members.

Lastly, for Objective #3 we can compare the vegetation recovery from the legacy, lower spatial- and spectral-resolution datasets to the higher resolution datasets used in this study. We can assess how the recovery scales from lower to higher resolution and what differences exist from each analysis.

Analysis and Discussion¶

Objective #1: Vegetation Analysis¶

We will use three different vegetation indices to evaluate the burned areas after the Chimney Tops 2 Fire.

  1. Normalized Burn Ratio (NBR)
  • NBR uses the spectral response of burned vegetation versus healthy vegetation to identify burned areas.
  1. Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI)
  • NDVI uses the spectral response of vegetation to quantify the greenness of an area.
  1. Modified Soil Adjusted Vegetation Index (MSAVI)
  • MSAVI is a vegetation index in which the soil-noise background is minimized using a factor that varies inversely with the amount of vegetation present (Qi et al., 199490134-1)).

Selection of Bands for Vegetation Analysis¶

The NEON imaging spectrometer measures 426 bands in the range of 383.5343 - 2511.8945 nm, in which each band has a band width of 5 nm.

  • For the calculation of NBR, we use band 117 for the NIR band and band 400 for the SWIR band. (vanGerrevink et al., 2021)
  • For the calculation of NDVI and MSAVI, we use band 58 for the Red band and band 84 for the NIR band. (Meng et al., 2018)

We subset and stack these bands in the following order:¶

  • Bands 58, 84, 117, 400; or Red, NIR (vegetation index), NIR (burn ratio), SWIR.
  • The vegetation analysis below will be conducted on one specific reflectance tile using data collected by the NEON Airborne Observation Platform. Here is a map showing the location of the tile within the Chimney Tops 2 fire boundary. The fire boundary is sourced from the "Monitoring Trends in Burn Severity" program.

1. Normalized Burn Ratio (NBR)¶

  • $NBR=\frac{(NIR-SWIR)}{(NIR+SWIR)}$
  • The Difference Normalized Burn Ratio (dNBR) is the difference between the pre-fire NBR and the post-fire NBR.
  • Here, we plot the difference normalized burn ratio of the Chimney Tops 2 Fire using reflectance data collected by the NEON Airborne Observation Platform. The plot of the difference between the pre-post NBR shows significant burned areas still exist almost one-year after the Chimney Tops 2 Fire. Regions above dNBR = 0.1 represent burn areas, whereas regions below dNBR = -0.1 represent regrowth.

2. Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI)¶

  • $NDVI=\frac{(NIR-Red)}{(NIR+Red)}$
  • The difference NDVI is the difference between the post-fire NDVI and the pre-fire NDVI.

3. Modified Soil Adjusted Vegetation Index (MSAVI)¶

  • The MSAVI equation has been expanded for ease of computation from its original form of $\frac{2NIR+1-\sqrt{(2NIR + 1)^{2}-8(NIR-Red)}}{2}$ to $NIR+0.5-0.5\sqrt{4NIR^{2}-4NIR+8Red+1}$
  • The difference MSAVI is the difference between the post-fire MSAVI and the pre-fire MSAVI.
  • On the left, we plot the difference normalized difference vegetation index (post-pre NDVI) of the Chimney Tops 2 Fire using reflectance data collected by the NEON Airborne Observation Platform. The plot of the post-pre NDVI shows remaining loss of greenness almost a year after the Chimney Tops 2 Fire. The most significant loss of vegetation are shown in pink.
  • On the right, we plot the difference modified soil adjusted vegetation index (post-pre MSAVI) using the reflectance data collected by the NEON Airborne Observation Platform. The difference in post-pre MSAVI plot shows that the Chimney Tops region is still showing vegetation recovery within one year after the fire. MSAVI takes into account the soil-noise background. Upon comparison with the difference NDVI, the difference MSAVI plot suggests that the vegetation regrowth is small, since the soil-noise background is significant.

# Import data from .csv files
# Note data were downloaded as .csv in FW13 format
# and therefore require a bunch of parsing

fw13_ig = os.path.join("raws",
                     "raws-fw13-407603-11282016-hourly.csv")


ig = pd.read_csv(fw13_ig,header=None,sep='\s+',dtype='string')

#Label first iteration of columns (tab/space separated only)
ig.columns = ["Site-Date-Time", "DryBulb", "RH-Wind Az", 
              "WndSpd", "MaxTemp","MinTemp", "MaxRH", 
              "MinRH","PrecipDur","Precp Amt-Flag","HerbGreenness",
              "SG-MT-MT-SC","Solar Rad-Gust Az", "Gust Avg-N Flag"]

#Parse Site and DateTime data from combined strings
ig["Site"]=ig['Site-Date-Time'].str[3:9].astype(int)
ig["DateTime"]=ig['Site-Date-Time'].str[9:21]
ig['DateTime']=pd.to_datetime(ig['DateTime'],format='%Y%m%d%H%M', )
ig = ig.set_index('DateTime')

#Parse RH and Wind Azimuth from combined strings
ig["RH"]=ig['RH-Wind Az'].str[0:2].astype(int)
ig["WindAz"]=ig['RH-Wind Az'].str[2:5].astype(int)

ig["GustAz"]=ig['Solar Rad-Gust Az'].str.slice(start=-3).astype(int)
ig["Solar Rad"]=ig['Solar Rad-Gust Az'].str.slice(stop=-3).astype(int)

ig['GustSpd']=ig['Gust Avg-N Flag'].str.slice(stop=-1).astype(int)

ig["WndSpd"]=ig["WndSpd"].astype(int)

#Remake .df with key variables
ig_parsed = ig[['Site','WindAz','WndSpd','GustAz','GustSpd','DryBulb','RH']]

mean_wind_az = ig_parsed['WindAz'].mean().astype(int)
mean_gust_az = ig_parsed['GustAz'].mean().astype(int)
print("The mean wind/gust azimuths on Nov 28 were",
      mean_wind_az,"/",mean_gust_az,"degrees")

# Calculate slope and aspect with rasterio
def calculate_slope(DEM):
    gdal.DEMProcessing('slope.tif', DEM, 'slope')
    with rasterio.open('slope.tif') as dataset:
        slope=dataset.read(1)
    return slope

def calculate_aspect(DEM):
    gdal.DEMProcessing('aspect.tif', DEM, 'aspect')
    with rasterio.open('aspect.tif') as dataset:
        aspect=dataset.read(1)
    return aspect

Summary and Future Directions¶

In this project, we aim to spatially quantify the vegetation recovery at 1-m spatial resolution, relate the variability in environmental fire effects, and relate these efforts towards each other. In this post, we have shown our first steps toward understanding the recovery after the Chimney Tops 2 Fire. With the vegetation analysis, we have found that even within one year after the fire, there are still significant burned areas within the Chimney Tops region. However, there is also evidence of regrowth, which in some areas may be minimal since the soil-noise background seems to be significant. For next steps, we will continue to survey the Chimney Tops region, and then we will compare the three vegetation indices and determine which best discriminates between unburned and burned areas using the Random Forest algorithm. Then we will use the NEON reflectance data and field data for vegetation type and cover for Great Smoky Mountains National Park (NEON Plant presence and percent cover: DP1.10058.001) and build a spectral library in order to conduct a spectral band analysis. This will allow us to classify the components within the burned region into separate components and possibly identify vegetation species remotely.
